# Commit Message Convention

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <summary>
```

## Types (mandatory prefix)

- `feat` — new feature or capability
- `fix` — bug fix
- `chore` — deps, config, tooling, cleanup
- `perf` — performance improvement
- `refactor` — code restructuring without behavior change
- `docs` — documentation only
- `style` — CSS/UI visual changes (no logic)
- `test` — adding or updating tests
- `a11y` — accessibility improvement

## Scopes (use when applicable)

`parsers`, `workers`, `ui`, `data`, `auth`, `stripe`, `map`, `seo`, `mobile`, `db`, `stablecoins`, `notion`

## Rules

1. **Language:** English only. No Russian, no mixed language.
2. **Title length:** ≤ 72 characters. No exceptions.
3. **Title format:** lowercase after colon. No period at end.
4. **Body:** use body (after blank line) for details if needed — never cram a list into the title.
5. **One logical change per commit.** If you need "and" in the title, it's probably two commits.

## Anti-patterns (NEVER do these)

- `куча всего на главной` — Russian, no prefix, vague
- `stats sction small fix` — typo, no prefix, unclear
- `Jurisdictions Entities` — no verb, no prefix, meaningless
- `1. Did X 2. Did Y 3. Did Z` — numbered list in title (use body)
- `feat: v1.9+ — SEO, UI redesign, paywall, pricing, header overhaul` — multiple unrelated features in one commit

## Good examples

```
feat(parsers): add Wave 4 parsers — US FDIC, GB PRA (+5176 entities)
fix(db): scope entity delete by parser_id to prevent data loss
perf(ui): route-level code splitting with React.lazy
style(mobile): pricing table responsive at 375px viewport
test(workers): add quality rules unit tests
chore: update Vite 6 → 7, regenerate lock file
```
